subsection.md:
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
\text{oriented coordinate area} \amp \text{positive normal} \amp \text{circulation density}\\ \hline
dy\wedge dz \amp \mathbf i \amp R_y-Q_z\\[1mm]
dz\wedge dx \amp \mathbf j \amp P_z-R_x\\[1mm]
dx\wedge dy \amp \mathbf k \amp Q_x-P_y
\end{array}

subsection.p:
Indeed, compute:

  d(P\,dx+Q\,dy+R\,dz) \amp= dP\wedge dx+dQ\wedge dy+dR\wedge dz
  \amp= (R_y-Q_z)\,dy\wedge dz
  \amp\quad+ (P_z-R_x)\,dz\wedge dx
  \amp\quad+ (Q_x-P_y)\,dx\wedge dy.

So

  \boxed{
  d\omega
  =
  \Phi_{\nabla\times\mathbf F}.
  }

In words:

  \boxed{
  \text{the exterior derivative of the work form is the flux form of the curl.}
  }

In classical vector notation, the same statement is

  \boxed{
  \oint_C \mathbf F\cdot d\mathbf r
  =
  \iint_D (\nabla\times\mathbf F)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,dS.
  }

